lab:
1. Create a new pod using the nginx image.
A: kubectl run nginx --image=nginx

2. Create a new pod with the name redis and the image redis123.
Utilize a pod-definition YAML file. Please note that the image name redis123 is intentionally incorrect. Do NOT correct the image at this stage; you will address this in the subsequent task.
A: can be done just by 'kubectl run redis --image=redis123'; if we want to generte a yaml file, we add '--dry-run=client -o yaml'; add a name '> redis-definition.yaml'
We use kubectl run command with --dry-run=client -o yaml option to create a manifest file :-
kubectl run redis --image=redis123 --dry-run=client -o yaml > redis-definition.yaml
After that, using kubectl create -f command to create a resource from the manifest file :-
kubectl create -f redis-definition.yaml 
Verify the work by running kubectl get command :-
kubectl get pods

3. Now change the image on this pod to redis.
Once done, the pod should be in a running state.
A: Use the kubectl edit command to update the image of the pod to redis.
kubectl edit pod redis
Alternatively, if you used a pod definition file then update the image from redis123 to redis in the definition file via Vi or Nano editor and then run kubectl apply command to update the image :-
kubectl apply -f redis-definition.yaml 






